  "prompt": "Is the test taker report for GMAT accessible immediately after the test ? It\u2019s not the official score report that GMAC sends after 15-20 days.",
  "response": "Yes, immediately after completing the GMAT, you will receive an **unofficial score report** on the test screen. This immediate feedback includes:\n\n1. **Total Score:** A combined score from the Quantitative and Verbal sections.\n2. **Section Scores:** Separate scores for the Quantitative and Verbal sections.\n3. **Integrated Reasoning (IR) Score:** Your performance in the IR section.\n4. **Analytical Writing Assessment (AWA) Score:** Your score for the essay component.\n\nHowever, it's important to note a few key points:\n\n- **Official Score Report:** While you receive the unofficial scores right after the test, the **official score report** from GMAC is typically available within **20 calendar days**. This official report is what you will send to business schools and includes a detailed breakdown of all sections, including percentile rankings.\n\n- **Score Verification:** If you choose to \"review\" any questions during the test, your scores might be delayed. Additionally, if you decide to cancel your scores immediately after the test, no scores will be reported to schools, and you'd need to retake the exam.\n\n- **Accessing Your Scores:** You can view your official scores by logging into your GMAT account on the [official GMAT website](https://www.mba.com/). Once available, you can send your scores to up to five programs for free on the day you take the test. Additional score reports can be sent for a fee.\n\n- **Score Components:** The immediate report provides a good overview, but the official score report includes more comprehensive data, such as command of grammar, critical reasoning skills, and other detailed metrics that can be valuable for your application process.\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Immediate Access:** Unofficial scores for Total, Quantitative, Verbal, IR, and AWA sections right after the test.\n- **Official Scores:** Detailed score report sent by GMAC within 20 days, necessary for official applications.\n\nFor the most accurate and personalized information, especially if there have been recent updates or changes, it's always a good idea to consult the [official GMAT website](https://www.mba.com/) or contact GMAC directly.",
